The 2025 NFL season commenced with Week 1 games on September 7, 2025. Notably, there was no Week 0 in the NFL schedule. Here are the recaps and key player statistics from the opening week:

**Jacksonville Jaguars 26, Carolina Panthers 10**

The Jaguars' defense, led by linebacker Foye Oluokun, dominated the Panthers, holding them without a touchdown until the final minutes. Oluokun recorded 10 tackles, an interception, and a forced fumble, contributing to 10 points for Jacksonville. Offensively, running back Travis Etienne Jr. rushed for 143 yards, including a 71-yard run that set up a touchdown. Quarterback Trevor Lawrence completed 19 of 31 passes for 178 yards, one touchdown, and an interception. Rookie wide receiver Brian Thomas Jr. added a 9-yard touchdown run. ([reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/sports/nfl/foye-oluokun-jaguars-defense-shut-down-panthers-season-opening-win--flm-2025-09-07/?utm_source=openai))

**Buffalo Bills 41, Baltimore Ravens 40**

In a thrilling matchup, the Bills edged out the Ravens. Quarterback Josh Allen delivered a historic performance, throwing for 394 yards and two touchdowns, while also rushing for two touchdowns. This marked his seventh game with at least two passing and two rushing touchdowns, the most in NFL history. Ravens quarterback Lamar Jackson nearly achieved a perfect passer rating, rushing for 70 yards and a touchdown. Running back Derrick Henry added 169 rushing yards and two touchdowns for Baltimore. ([nfl.com](https://www.nfl.com/news/nfl-stats-and-records-week-1-bills-qb-josh-allen-has-historic-performance-vs-ravens?utm_source=openai))

**Pittsburgh Steelers 23, New York Jets 20 (OT)**

Steelers quarterback Aaron Rodgers, at 41 years old, threw four touchdown passes in his debut, tying Tom Brady for the most such games in NFL history. Jets quarterback Justin Fields showcased his dual-threat ability, passing for 218 yards and a touchdown, and rushing for 48 yards and two touchdowns. The game concluded with a game-sealing pass breakup by Steelers cornerback Jalen Ramsey. ([nfl.com](https://www.nfl.com/news/2025-nfl-season-week-1-what-we-learned-from-sunday-s-games?utm_source=openai))

**Miami Dolphins 36, Los Angeles Chargers 34**

Dolphins quarterback Tua Tagovailoa threw for 466 yards and three touchdowns, with wide receiver Tyreek Hill recording 11 receptions for 215 yards and two touchdowns. Chargers quarterback Justin Herbert passed for 228 yards and a touchdown, while running back Austin Ekeler contributed 117 rushing yards and a touchdown. ([thehuddle.com](https://thehuddle.com/lists/481343/?utm_source=openai))

**Dallas Cowboys 40, New York Giants 0**

The Cowboys' defense dominated, recording seven sacks, two interceptions, a fumble recovery, a defensive touchdown, and a special teams touchdown. Offensively, quarterback Dak Prescott threw for 143 yards, and running back Tony Pollard added 70 rushing yards and two touchdowns. Giants quarterback Daniel Jones struggled, throwing for 104 yards with two interceptions and fumbling twice. ([thehuddle.com](https://thehuddle.com/lists/481343/?utm_source=openai))

**Philadelphia Eagles 38, Detroit Lions 35**

Eagles quarterback Jalen Hurts passed for 243 yards, and running back Miles Sanders rushed for 96 yards and a touchdown. Lions quarterback Jared Goff threw for 215 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception, while running back D'Andre Swift rushed for 144 yards and a touchdown. ([sportsrec.com](https://www.sportsrec.com/nfl-football-week-1-scores-stats-fantasy-leaders-8675309.html?utm_source=openai))

**New England Patriots 20, Las Vegas Raiders 13**

Patriots quarterback Mac Jones threw for 213 yards, a touchdown, and an interception. Running back Damien Harris added 48 rushing yards. Raiders quarterback Jimmy Garoppolo passed for 250 yards and two touchdowns. ([patriots.com](https://www.patriots.com/news/gamebook-full-patriots-panthers-stats?utm_source=openai))

These matchups set the tone for an exciting NFL season ahead.

fields.email_text:
Subject: Week 1 Recap: A Fun Start! -- RESEND

Hey y'all. Apologies for the duplicate email. When I sent the last one, I noticed a glitch that prevents you from "replying all" to the email. I'd like for us to be able to carry on conversations through the season. It should be enabled now. Thanks!

Hey Team,

And we're off! Week 1 is in the books. This week, Paul, Ben, and I secured the top spot with **16 points** proving, in my case anyway, that even a blind squirrel finds a nut once in a while. Jennifer and Laura aren't far behind with **14 points** each, while a quartet of Lattimores is right on their heels with **13 points** (Alan, Leonard, Barbara, and Stephen). Good shows, but the season is young. Very young.

Josh Allen's performance has to be the highlight of the week, don't you agree? 394 yards, two TDs in the air, another two on the ground. Allen holds the NFL record for most games (seven) with at least two passing and two rushing TDs.

Speaking of records, I thought Jalen Carter's ejection six seconds into the Dallas/Philly game had to be a record. It wasn't. That honor belongs to Pittsburgh linebacker Joey Porter and Browns running back William Green who were ejected in 2004 for fighting during warm-ups. That's a thing you now know.

Week 2 picks are open. Let's see what we all learned last week.

Cheers,  
Mark

p.s. Let me know if you see any errors in your scores.

Subject: Week 2 Reminder

## Week 2 is here!

#### Week 1 was an exciting start, but it's left us with some lingering questions:   

- Will Josh Allen continue his (1 game) bid for this year's MVP?  
- Can Mike McDaniel survive the growing, pitchfork-wielding mob in Miami?  
- Will Jalen Carter make it to the first snap this week?  
- Can the Panthers figure out how to play something resembling the game of football?  


If you haven't gotten your Week 2 picks in, remember that you have until 7pm tonight, so get it done and let's get some answers.

Cheers!  
Mark

Subject: Weekly Recap: Touchdowns and Triumphs!

Hey Team,

What a thrilling week we just had! Ethan led the charge with a solid **14 points**, narrowly edging out Hilary with **13**. Ben, Jamie, and John all pulled in **12 points**, proving that competition is heating up. A special shoutout to Ethan for his impressive pickshes clearly got a knack for predicting winners! 

For those who didnt quite hit the mark this week, remember, even the best players have off days. Denny and Susan, you're still in the gametheres plenty of time to turn things around. Just think of it as your underdog story waiting to unfold!

As we gear up for next week, lets keep the momentum going. And remember, no spitting on opponents, even if its just for fun! Keep those picks coming, and may the best predictor win!

Cheers,  
Mark

Subject: Weekly Recap: The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly!

Hey everyone,

Well, it looks like Week 3 was a *real nail-biter*or maybe just a nail-breaker for some of us! With no winners declared this week, it seems weve all taken a collective hit. But lets not dwell on the negatives! Kudos to Ethan, Ben, and Alan for their stellar ability to pick... nothing! Just kidding! You guys are still in the game, and thats what counts.

Looking at the overall standings, Paul is still leading the pack with a total of 31 pointsway to go, Paul! Laura and I are hot on his heels, tied at 29 points. For those who might be feeling a little down about this week, remember: every week is a fresh start! So dust off those crystal balls and lets see if we can turn it around next week.

Keep those picks coming, and may the odds be ever in your favor!

Cheers,  
Mark

Subject: And That's Week 2  

We had some movement during week 2. **Ethan and Hilary captured this week's top two spots** after finishing 12th and 15th (respectively) last week, catapulting Ethan to 5th overall and Hilary to 12th. They both found value where no one else did, Ethan being the only one of us who selected Seattle and Hilary the only one with faith in the Falcons. Nice job, y'all!

I wanted to point out two new features to the site that went live this morning.  

- You can now make partial picks, save them, then come back later to finish (before, you had to pick every game for your picks to save).   

- You now have the option to have your picks emailed to you (handy if you want an independent record of your picks or if you're one of those accountant types who run an audit every week). Just click the button next to "Email me a copy of my picks" prior to clicking "Save Picks."  

Both of these features were the result of feedback I received from some of you. If you have any suggestions, don't be shy.

Week 3 is live, so take a look at your scouting reports and let's play some football. Have a great week!

Cheers!  
Mark

Subject: Week 3 Already!

Greetings all! Hope you've had a stellar week so far. Just a reminder that Week 3 is upon us. Miami and Buffalo kick off the week's festivities tonight, so get your picks in by 7pm and enjoy the game!

Cheers!  
Mark

Subject: Great Minds Think Alike  

Greetings all. I just noticed something that merited a mid-week email.  

My cousin, Nicole, and I often say about each other "Great minds think alike. And so do ours." Well, there's a lot of "alike" thinking in this week's picks. We have *all* picked the same winner in 7 of this week's 16 games. So I guess time will tell whether we *all* fall into the "great minds" or the "so do ours" category.  

Enjoy the rest of your week.

Cheers!  
Mark

fields.email_text:
Subject: Week 3: The Scourge of Kickers

Hey Team,

Not a great week to be a field goal unit. Sunday recorded the most blocked field goals in a single day (in the NFL), with four, two of which were returned for touchdowns. Special shoutout to Philly defensive tackle, **Jordan Davis**, who did it all in one play--blocked the kicked, recovered the ball, and carried it to the house for a good, old-fashioned scoop and score. I love to see a big man make his way into the scoring stats!

Also not a great week to be an Atlanta Falcon. I just don't know what to say. Happy for my Panthers but truly befuddled. 

As a group, we went 5-2 in the games for which we all picked the same winner, with Carolina (gasp!) and Cleveland coming through as the big spoilers.

**Ben** took first this week with 15 points, with Mark W finishing just one point behind. Paul, Susan, Ethan, and yours truly rounded out the top three, each finishing with 13 points.

As we dive deeper into the season, its great to see some of you improving week over week. **Ethan** picked his way up to 4th overall with two solid weeks in a row.

Lets gear up for Week 4! 

Cheers,  
Mark

Subject: Weekly Recap  What a Week!

Hey Team,

Well, week 4 was a bit of a snooze-fest, wasnt it? With no winners in sight, it seems like we all collectively decided to take a week off! But dont fret; the thrill of next weeks games is just around the corner. Shoutout to **Ben**, **Paul**, and **Ethan** for still managing to rack up some points last week, even if it was a big fat zero! Remember, every week is a fresh startso lets shake off this one and come back swinging!

Looking at the overall standings, **Ben** is still leading the pack with 45 points, followed closely by **Paul** at 44. But hey, **Mark** isnt far behind with 42 pointskeep those picks coming! And for those who might be feeling a bit down after this week, remember: even the best teams have off days. Just dust off those picks and lets aim for a comeback next week!

Catch you all on the flip side!

Cheers,  
Mark

Subject: Week 4

Just a friendly reminder, you've got a little over 5 hours to get this week's picks in.   
Good luck!

Cheers!  
Mark

Subject: Week 4 is in the Books!  

Let's start out with a little "do you know" segment. Do you know what a *scorigami* is? I didn't until Ethan introduced me to the idea a year or two ago. A *scorigami* is a score that has never before happened in the NFL. Green Bay and Dallas gave us the second *scorigami* of the season, with a 40-40 tie (Buffalo's 41-40 win over Baltimore in Week 1 was the first). If you have any desire to learn more about this interesting but utterly useless stat, check out [https://nflscorigami.com](https://nflscorigami.com)). Class dismissed. Now to last week.   

The Giants duped all of us by losing to the Chargers, a game none of us picked correctly. And the Panthers continue to break hearts across the Carolinas. Special condolences to **Stephen** and **Pam** who seemed to be really torn up over it.   

I've talked before about great minds thinking alike. With an 8-way tie for first place this week, it seems a lot of you were dialed into each other. Overall, **Ben** and **Paul** hang on to the top two spots and **Ethan** continues his climb, up to 3rd from 4th last week.

A couple of housekeeping matters.  

- First, following another user suggestion, your "Past Picks" list is now (I think) easier to read and a little better organized.   

- Second, I will be in the mountains Wednesday through Sunday, staying at a B&B with no TVs. I'll still have internet access, but I may be slow in updating results.   

Have a great week!

Cheers!

Mark

Subject: Week 5 Picks  

Good Thursday morning to you from scenic Bryson City, NC! Week 5 is here. Be sure to get your picks in by 7pm and let's play some football!  

Cheers!

Mark

Subject: Vegas Lost

I don't have a lot to say about this week's games -- didn't see a single one. The Panthers have given some of us new hope -- or is it false hope? The week proved that sports gambling is ... well ... still gambling. Vegas went 6-8. Leonard & Barbara and Ethan both bucked the odds and were rewarded well -- Leonard & Barbara being the only one to pick the Thursday night game and Ethan the only one to pick the Monday night game. And the season goes on.

**A Little Housekeeping**  
At some point this week, you'll see a new tab showing League Standings, both by division and overall. In addition, the picks page will show team records. Two things  

- **Do not** rely on any of the records or rankings this week as they may not be accurate until I complete the rollout (which I hope to have finished before this weekend).   
- Teams are ranked solely by winning percentage of games they've played (so, for example, a 1-0 team would be ranked higher than a 3-1 team) and there are no tie-breakers built in. *Don't be surprised if official rankings are a different.* This is only meant to give you a general idea of how the league is stacking up.  

That about covers it. Have a great week, all!  

Cheers!

Mark

Subject: Week 6 Is Over and I Don't Understand Football  

So that's another one down and it proved more than ever that this is anybody's year. You know, I played football from the time I was 8 years old until I graduated high school. I've followed it ever since. I'm no expert but at 54 years old, I like to think I know something about the game. I guess I just don't understand it anymore. In what football world do the Panthers beat the Cowboys, the Chiefs beat the Lions, the Bears beat the Commanders, and Falcons beat the Bills, **all in the same week**? 

Mark W saw it coming, though, being the only person to pick the Bears, catapulting him to the top of the weekly rankings. The top of the season board hasn't changed a lot but if we have many more weeks like this one, I expect some major shuffling.

Hope everyone has a great week!

Cheers!  
Mark

Subject: Week 7 Games	  

Greetings, all, and happy Thursday! Just a reminder to get your picks in by 7pm tonight. When I checked a few minutes ago, we were missing picks from 4 people.  

Have a great evening!  

Mark

Subject: Week 8

Friendly reminder to get this week's picks in by 7pm today.  

And another friendly reminder for those who haven't yet submitted their $10 entry, please get that in when you can.  

Hope everyone has a great week!  

Cheers!  
Mark

Subject: Week 12  

Hello all and Happy Friday! I just wanted to take a sec and apologize for some of the late game updates this time around. It's been a weird week in the (Mark and Amy) Lattimore house. I should be able to regroup and update everything (including putting the picks in for those of you who had to email them to me) tonight or (more likely) tomorrow. Have a fantastic weekend!  

Cheers!  
Mark

Subject: Happy Thanksgiving, All!  

The season is flying by as we roll into Week 13. This is a big week. There are five 2 point games--3 on Thursday, 1 on Friday, and the Monday night game. If you want to make a major move in the standings, this is the week to do it.  NOTE: the first game Thursday starts at 1pm eastern, so have your picks in by then. The window will close at 1pm Thursday.  

A bit of housekeeping. If you're having trouble getting your picks in either because of technical issues or internet access, please shoot me a text rather than email (if you can). You're likely to get a faster response. My number is (864) 421-3610. I don't have everyone's number saved, so please identify yourself when you text me.

Best of luck and a very Happy Thanksgiving to all!  

Cheers!  
Mark

Subject: Pick Window  

If anyone has tried to log in to make picks in the last 90 minutes, you've probably been locked out. Sorry about that. I never reset the site to the regular schedule after Thanksgiving. You should be able to get in to make picks now. Shoot me a text at 864-421-3610 if you have any problems. Again, my apologies.  

Thanks!

Mark

Subject: Week 17 Picks  

Merry Christmas Eve, all! Hope you're all gearing up for a great Christmas day.  

The first game tomorrow starts at 1pm, so you need to have your picks in by then. Sorry for the late email -- frankly, I just thought about it. If you have any issues, shoot me a text at 864-421-3610.  

Merry Christmas!

Mark

fields.email_text:
Subject: Weekly Recap: The Thrilling Week 18!

Hey Team,

Well, Week 18 was a *real humdinger*! Sadly, it seems like everyone decided to take a week off from picking winners, as nobody scored any points. Jamie, Alan, Paul, Mark, Stephen, and the rest of the gang all ended up with a big fat zero. Its like we collectively decided to play the guess the winner game, and we all guessed wrong! 

In the grand scheme of things, Jennifer continues to hold the lead with 199 points, closely followed by Paul at 198 and Jamie at 197. But dont fret if youre lagging behind! Theres always next week to make a comeback. Remember, even the best teams have their off daysjust look at the last-minute fumbles! Keep your spirits high, and lets aim to turn those zeroes into heroics next time.

Cheers,  
Mark

Subject: Week 18!  

Well, we made it. Last week of the regular season. Sure there are a lot of questions and possibilities going into week 18, but the only one I'm concerned with is will the Panthers make the playoffs. We'll know in a few days.  

There is no Thursday night game this week. The first game kicks off at 4:30pm Saturday (Eastern), so the pick window will close at 4pm Saturday. Be sure to get your picks in by then.  

Good luck all!  

Mark

Subject: And that's a wrap for the regular season!  

Well, we reached the end. That's a wrap on the 2025-26 regular season. It's been a blast. I'll be sending out another email in the next day or two with "official" regular season results (there's a tie for third and I need to calculate the tie-breaker, which I hope to get to tonight).  

That said, it's wildcard week. I should have the schedule put in by Wednesday. Once it's up, I'll shoot out another email and will include the post-season scoring rules. Until then, good luck to all returning to the first full week of work in a while. I've got a coffee IV going, so here's to Monday!  

Oh, and go Panthers! (and thank you, ATL).

Cheers! 

Mark

fields.notes:
Dallas @ Philly: Jalen Carter was ejected 6 seconds into the game for spitting on Dak Prescott. Fun fact: while that was an early ejection, it's not even close to the earliest ejection on record. That distinction belongs to Pittsburgh Steelers linebacker Joey Porter and Cleveland Browns running back William Green who were ejected in 2004 for fighting during warm-ups.

Great quote: Ray Lewis talking about what he likes about the Ravens defense: "The pieces that we have now, you don't have to coach them, just unleash them."
